text.__SUMMARY__: Corymbia watsoniana, commonly known as the large-fruited yellowjacket or watson's yellow bloodwood', is a bloodwood native to Queensland.
text.Taxonomy: The species was first formally described by the botanist Ferdinand von Mueller in 1877 as Eucalyptus watsoniana as part of the work Fragmenta Phytographiae Australiae It was reclassified as Corymbia watsoniana in 1995 by Kenneth Hill and Lawrence Alexander Sidney Johnson in 1995 as part of the work Systematic studies in the eucalypts. A revision of the bloodwoods, genus Corymbia (Myrtaceae) as published in the journal Telopea.
